[25] The cumulative effect of the evidence of SP2 which stands
largely unchallenged to our mind establishes beyond reasonable
doubt the positive identification of the appellant.
[26] The identification of the appellant by SP2 was not only made
through the dock but also at the earlier identification parade at the
police station. The law pertaining to identification is clear in that
dock identification is a piece of substantive evidence. Evidence
pertaining to identification parade provides corroborative evidence
of the substantive evidence of dock identification. (see Budhsen v.
State of Uttar Pradesh [1970] Cr LJ 1149; Malkansingh v. State of
Madhya Pradesh [2003] Cr LJ 3535).
[27] In conclusion we do not find any appealable error on the part of
the learned trial judge and we see no ground for contending that the
conviction is unsatisfactory or unsafe. The appeal is accordingly
dismissed and the conviction and sentence of the High Court
affirmed.

